		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/17/blogs/motherlode-tiffanie/motherlode-tiffanie-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/17/blogs/motherlode-tiffanie/motherlode-tiffanie-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/03/17/blogs/motherlode-tiffanie/motherlode-tiffanie-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000002772647" width="592" height="444" alt="The author and her son."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="444"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">The author and her son.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Courtesy of Tiffanie DiDonato.</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//parenting.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/03/23/i-didnt-want-my-son-to-have-dwarfism-not-really/" data-title="I Didn&#8217;t Want My Son to Have Dwarfism. Not Really." data-description="I have rare form of dwarfism, and I never expected to be able to have a childâbut once I was pregnant, part of me expected my son to share my condition. I wasn&#039;t sure I&#039;d know how to raise a &quot;normal&quot; child. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>Pregnant? Me? Not going to happen. Or so I thought.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As the only person in my family with a rare form of dwarfism, diastrophic dysplasia, I spent my childhood fighting joint pain and muscle stiffness and enduring multiple bone corrective surgeries. I played with dolls when I could, but pretending to be a mommy didnât seem right. Even after I gained 14 inches through a grueling (and highly controversial) limb-lengthening procedure, my body simply wasnât like other girls&#8217;. Although the idea seemed beautiful, being a mother didnât seem to be a part of my future.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">So when my husband, a 6-foot tall, dark and handsome Marine, returned from his second tour in Iraq, we didnât  start having a conversation about having children â we avoided one. But every time Eric saw a little boy in a mini New York Yankees jersey, I could see his longing, and I also saw his fear in broaching the subject of having a child with me.  I had said I probably couldnât carry a baby, so he didnât want to hurt my feelings. He needed to protect me from pain, so he supplied excuses convenient to both of us. âThe economy is too uncertain right now for children,â he would say. &#8220;Letâs wait until Iâm promoted.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">We were very careful.  But life had other plans for us. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For me, learning I had a baby on the way meant more than finding a theme for a nursery or sifting through books on baby names. It meant a reason to panic. Could I carry to term? Could I deliver safely? I didnât have the luxury of simply being pregnant. I was labeled a high-risk mother, and my baby was labeled a high-risk baby. My doctor was concerned that there would be no room for a child to grow inside me, that my breathing would grow increasingly difficult. âIf we can make it to where your baby is three pounds, Iâll be happy,â she said.<span id="more-50032"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Then there was the million-dollar question: Would our baby have a dwarfism, too?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The world did not hesitate to let us know its wishes for us: no dwarf baby! That isn&#8217;t surprising. Itâs a life of struggle and pain. Eric especially didnât want to see anyone, least of all his child, endure the same brutal fight I had endured to obtain independence. Family and friends concurred. No one wanted a child like me.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On the outside I understood that their feelings pertained to the condition of dwarfism. And yet, on the inside I wondered something far more troubling. What did it mean to be me, anyway?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For the first time I thought about dwarfism not just as a condition, but as an identity, my identity. Here was the dilemma: Was my ability to be strong, unyielding and creative because I had dwarfism? Or was it because I had the privilege of having G.I. Jane for a mother? Were my triumphs in life because I was handicapped, and therefore people had gone easy on me, or because I deserved them? More than this, would I be a good mother because I was different? Or would I fail, because I was different? Iâm confident as a person with my form of dwarfism. I know nothing else. But I will never let dwarfism define me.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Along the way, no one bothered to ask what I was afraid of. It wasnât that I would have a child like me. It was that I would have one who was very different. Once we got the results, one of us, my husband or me, would know we faced that challenge.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Eventually, we found out: no dwarfism. Normal. Not like me.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Intellectually I was thrilled for my unborn son. Emotionally I worried about all the ways we wouldnât be able to connect. I had to accept from the onset something that  every parent learns eventually: Our children arenât us. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I named my son Titan,  and you can bet there is a bit of wish fulfillment in there: the child of a dwarf, named after a race of giants with supernatural strength.  </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But  it turns out that I named him well, and maybe too well. He is unusually speedy and athletic, a constant blur of mischief and activity. Every day is a game of wits. Every chance Titan has, he is climbing higher than my head, cramming himself into deep corners out of my reach, running faster than I can follow and challenging the grasp of my arthritic fingers. Many days, all I can do is stay nearby, monitor and wait. I have to be more patient than most, and louder. My voice has had to become more ominous.  My âTITAN, NO!â must mean something. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When Titan traces the cavernous scars, vestiges of the limb-lengthening surgeries, that snake down my legs, Iâm suffused with love for his perfect little body. But a certain trepidation exists, too. One day Iâll explain those scars. One day Iâll explain the pregnancy. And heâll understand, too, that I maneuver through the world with pain and discomfort, but also with great joy and appreciation. His own trials may not be physical, but he is human and he will have them. I donât worry as much about our connection anymore. After all, connecting is not so much about similarity as it is about a love and appreciation for what makes us singular.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Tiffanie DiDonato is the author of &#8220;Dwarf: How One Woman Fought for a Body â and a Life â She Was Never Supposed to Have.&#8221; She plans to have  another child. </em></p>
	</div>
